      <div class="sumarry-link-wrap">
      <a href="#" class="article-summary-link">Article Summary and Author Biography</a>      <div class="field-article-summary-hidden"><div class="field-article-summary-hidden-inner"><span class="field field-type-text field-field-article-summary"><p>Conventional wisdom says the state can best foster innovation by just getting out of the way. In fact, government has historically served not as a meddler in the private sector but as a key booster of it—and often a daring one, willing to take risks that businesses won’t.</p>
</span><span class="field field-type-text field-field-article-bio"><p>MARIANA MAZZUCATO is Professor of the Economics of Innovation in the Science Policy Research Unit at the University of Sussex. She is the author of <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Entrepreneurial-State-Debunking-Private-Economics/dp/0857282522/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1418255036&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=Entrepreneurial+State%3A+Debunking+Public+vs.+Private+Sector+Myths"><strong><em>The Entrepreneurial State: Debunking Public vs. Private Sector Myths</em></strong></a>.</p>
